    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "618c603a3dad5233",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "618c603a3dad5233",
        "text": "Again, on the one hand, it is the physical and mental development parameters (height, weight gain), nutrition, sensory functions, organ functions, blood values and skeleton, childhood diseases, physical, mental and social skills) that can be recorded - and in some cases are prescribed for recording by the authorities, which make available the multiple processes of growing up, first along the first dimension (visibility), but also with the intention to intervene and control, if necessary (third dimension), to ensure \"age-appropriate development\" and \"early detection of diseases requiring treatment\" or of \"delays or abnormalities.\" In this context, the child's development is monitored in a whole series of medical examinations that resemble a \"monitoring program.\" On the other hand, there are also countless advisors and support programs that are supposed to promote each individual developmental step and steer it on the right track. As in the case of the birth process or safety technology, fear seems to increase rather than decrease with the recording and controllability of many processes. On the one hand, it manifests itself in the parents' concern that they will have to seek \"medical advice\" for every discomfort, every scratch, every abnormality in the child's growth, speech, movement or communication. This form of dependence on apparatuses and experts undermines parental expectations of self-efficacy and, subsequently, experience of self-efficacy. It is not they themselves who listen to the child's needs and then seek and find an answer to them (in resonance with the child himself), but it is the doctors and experts who act on the basis of secure data and thus make the developmental processes as available as possible."
      },
      "after": "4d27372e12d51c98",
      "date": 1670009510178
