    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "ccac67d33b9cb2ce",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "ccac67d33b9cb2ce",
        "text": "The question of the medical-technical making available of bodily processes basically arises with every single medical intervention, for example, when it comes to the question of braces, antibiotics or, above all, vaccinations. The bitter dispute that has been fought for decades over the question of vaccination against childhood diseases seems to me to mark here, as it were, the cultural front line between the \"ideology of making available\" and the \"ideology of natural resonance\". Should the child and its body find the right answers on their own, or should the otherwise unpredictable dangers be eliminated by medical intervention? It may seem that from a resonance-theoretical perspective one must necessarily argue for the first option, but this conclusion is premature: the tremendous successes of modernity, not only of medicine, in making natural processes available have led to the scientific, technical, medical, and also political advances that have created, opened, and secured resonant spaces for many people in many contexts. Medical interventions that preserve hearing or sight, to name two extreme examples, are certainly among the enabling factors of resonance. Conversely, unavailability per se - for example, dying powerless from appendicitis without medical assistance - certainly does not mean the deepening of resonance relationships. Once again, the considerations made here are not an ethical plea, but they serve a diagnosis of the (constantly shifting) front lines between what we want to and can make available and what we want and have to find existential answers to as \"unavailability\", and also an identification of the social manifestations of the basic conflict between resonance longing and availability desire.\n"
      },
