      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "7c54ebddae0b3067",
        "text": "However, the desire to control and steer the child's developmental processes goes far beyond the medical/physical aspects; it reveals itself as a pressure to optimize almost all of the child's expressions of life. How do I ensure that he or she is optimally nourished, moves sufficiently and correctly, sleeps healthily, speaks correctly, develops his or her musical and athletic abilities, unfolds his or her intellectual potential, and increases his or her emotional and social intelligence? All of these development dimensions are now \"parameterized\" in one form or another, i.e., made quantitatively measurable, and there are again countless guidebooks, experts and support programs for each one. Ironically, most of them recommend \"listening to the child and his or her needs,\" but this listening is in competition with the experts' \"measuring\" and \"comparing,\" and advisors and programs always tend to determine or at least suggest the answers to be given.\n"
